---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="China Discovery Hub is a hand-curated, open-source directory of the best resources to discover China — built as a calmer doorway for the curious world."
>
  <article class="container-page py-16 max-w-prose">
    <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-accent">About</p>
    <h1 class="mt-3 font-serif text-4xl font-semibold leading-tight tracking-tight sm:text-5xl">
      A calmer doorway into China.
    </h1>

    <div class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-headings:font-serif prose-headings:tracking-tight max-w-none mt-10 prose-a:text-accent prose-a:no-underline hover:prose-a:underline">
      <p>
        In January 2025, hundreds of thousands of "TikTok refugees" landed on
        Xiaohongshu (RedNote). For the first time, ordinary internet users
        from outside China sat in the same comment threads as ordinary internet
        users inside it — exchanging pet photos, recipe questions, study tips,
        and "what's it like over there?" stories. The world's curiosity about
        China is back, in a more humane shape than the cable-news version.
      </p>

      <p>
        But the resources to actually <em>satisfy</em> that curiosity are
        scattered. A great Cantonese cooking channel here. A grammar wiki
        there. A long-form China podcast somewhere on a forum. Wikipedia
        articles that assume you already know things. Reddit threads that get
        buried within a week.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>China Discovery Hub</strong> is a single, calm directory of
        the resources we'd actually hand a curious friend. Hand-picked.
        Open to community submissions. No tracking, no algorithm,
        no signup.
      </p>

      <p>
        If you want the longer story behind the project — what was cut,
        what we got wrong, why hand-curation can do what algorithms can't —
        read{' '}
        <a href="/featured/building-china-discovery-hub">the founding essay</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>What we curate</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Language</strong> — apps, dictionaries, courses, listening practice.</li>
        <li><strong>Culture & history</strong> — primary sources, podcasts, accessible scholarship.</li>
        <li><strong>Food</strong> — real regional cuisines, recipe channels, sourcing.</li>
        <li><strong>Travel</strong> — visas, transport, city guides, payment apps for tourists.</li>
        <li><strong>Living in China</strong> — visas, banking, healthcare, expat communities.</li>
        <li><strong>Apps & platforms</strong> — how the Chinese internet actually works.</li>
        <li><strong>Entertainment</strong> — C-dramas, films, music, donghua animation.</li>
        <li><strong>Business & tech</strong> — leading companies, AI, EVs, cross-border.</li>
        <li><strong>Media & news</strong> — diverse English-language perspectives.</li>
        <li><strong>Diaspora</strong> — Chinese cultures, far from home.</li>
        <li><strong>Subcultures</strong> — Hanfu, guochao, citywalk, ACG, esports.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Editorial principles</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <strong>Cultural first, political second.</strong> We don't take
          sides on geopolitics. We <em>do</em> share resources from across the
          spectrum so readers can triangulate.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Quality before quantity.</strong> Every entry needs to be
          something a friend would actually thank you for sending. Broken
          links, dead projects and pure aggregators get cut.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Accessible to outsiders.</strong> If a resource requires
          fluent Mandarin or a Chinese mobile number to use, we flag that
          clearly so readers know what they're getting into.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Editorial picks are not advertisements.</strong> Featured
          slots are chosen by editors. If we ever experiment with affiliate
          links on commercial resources, or with clearly-labeled sponsored
          listings, that will be disclosed prominently and never disguised
          as editorial.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Open source.</strong> The site, its content, and its build
          process are all public on GitHub. Every resource is a markdown
          file anyone can read, audit or improve.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Frequently asked</h2>

      <h3>How is this different from Wikipedia?</h3>
      <p>
        Wikipedia is comprehensive and neutral. We're opinionated and
        compact. The job here is to say <em>"if you only have time for one
        thing in food, watch Chinese Cooking Demystified"</em> — something a
        neutrality-bound encyclopedia structurally can't do.
      </p>

      <h3>Why no individual creators or YouTubers as standalone entries?</h3>
      <p>
        Sites and institutions are different in character from personal
        voices, and putting one creator's YouTube channel next to a museum
        collection flattens both. A dedicated <em>Creators</em> section is
        planned. For now, individual creators get name-dropped inside
        editorial essays rather than listed as directory entries.
      </p>

      <h3>How do you handle politically sensitive resources?</h3>
      <p>
        "Balanced China coverage" is itself politically loaded — every
        editorial choice is read as a position. We try to include resources
        from multiple credible perspectives (PRC, diaspora, Hong Kong, Taiwan,
        Western academia, independent analysts) rather than picking a
        side. We <em>do</em> exclude outright propaganda from any direction.
      </p>

      <h3>How do you keep the directory up to date?</h3>
      <p>
        A weekly GitHub Action runs a link checker across every URL on the
        site. Broken links are filed as issues and fixed before deploy.
        Beyond that, every change goes through editorial review — community
        submissions and PRs included.
      </p>

      <h3>Can I suggest a resource or fix something?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes — please. Use the{' '}
        <a href="/submit">submit form</a>{' '}
        for the easy path, or open a PR / issue at{' '}
        <a href="https://github.com/pkloving/china-discovery-hub" rel="noopener noreferrer">
          github.com/pkloving/china-discovery-hub
        </a>{' '}
        if you're already on GitHub.
      </p>

      <h2>Who's behind this</h2>
      <p>
        Built and currently edited by{' '}
        <a href="https://github.com/pkloving" rel="noopener noreferrer">
          pkloving on GitHub
        </a>{' '}
        — a Mandarin learner with a bookmark-folder problem. The plan is to
        grow into a small editorial group over time; for now, every entry
        and every essay on the site goes through one editor's hands. PRs and
        critical feedback from people who know corners of China better than
        I do are very welcome.
      </p>

      <h2>How the site is built</h2>
      <p>
        Astro 5 + Tailwind, with every resource as a markdown file in a
        public GitHub repo. Search runs entirely in your browser via{' '}
        <a href="https://pagefind.app/" rel="noopener noreferrer">Pagefind</a>
        {' '}— no backend, no database, no API calls. Hosted on Cloudflare
        Pages for global edge delivery.
      </p>

      <h3>Privacy</h3>
      <p>
        We use Cloudflare Web Analytics (no cookies, no fingerprinting, no
        cross-site tracking) and that's the entire telemetry stack. No
        accounts. No newsletter pop-ups. No retargeting pixels. If you spot
        anything that looks like tracking on this site, please open an
        issue — it shouldn't be there.
      </p>

      <h2>Contact</h2>
      <p>
        Send corrections, recommendations or partnership ideas via the{' '}
        <a href="/submit">submit form</a>, or open an issue / PR on the
        GitHub repo.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
